        "materials_required": [
            "Old optical mouse (that works)",
            "Assorted bits of plastic from the recycle (bottle caps and rings)",
            "Ping-Pong ball or similar round object",
            "Wood, clay, or some other suitable material for a base",
            "Electrical wire (24 AWG stranded core)",
            "Paracord or a bootlace",
            "Green LEDs, 6x 3mm and 2x 5mm",
            "10k trimmer potentiometer",
            "SPDT switch",
            "Green and black gloss spray paints",
            "Cyanoacrylate glue"
        ],
        "description": "This project aims to create a functional and aesthetically pleasing trackball mouse from recycled and readily available materials. By utilizing the optical sensing system from an old mouse and crafting a custom enclosure and trackball guide, the project provides a cost-effective and environmentally friendly alternative to commercially available trackball mice.",
        "steps": [
            "Gather all necessary materials, including an old optical mouse, assorted plastic pieces, a ping-pong ball, base material (wood or clay), electrical wire, paracord, LEDs, potentiometer, switch, and spray paints.",
            "Disassemble the old mouse, keeping all parts. Separate the circuit board and the outer shell, focusing on extracting the optical port and scroll wheel axle guide.",
            "Cut apart the upper section of the mouse to get left and right finger rests, and the guide for clicker pads. Cut the clicker pad part as well as the corresponding guide neatly in half. Glue each clicker pad to its respective guide.",
            "Desolder microswitches and the scroll wheel encoder from the circuit board and resolder them with wires to allow for repositioning. Mount the scroll wheel encoder and 'middle click' switch to the axle guide.",
            "Test the circuit board to ensure it is functional. If not, replace it with a working one from another mouse.  Solder a jumper across the resistor port, and then solder two long wires to the LED port.",
            "Extend the mouse cord by soldering it to an old Apple charging cable, threading it through paracord for durability and aesthetics.",
            "Create a trackball guide by cutting a hole in the palm rest piece of the original mouse. Use snips and an X-acto knife to slowly create the perfect hole, ensuring smooth ball movement.",
            "Glue a round ring of plastic around the optical port. Assemble the interface by gluing the clicker pads, trackball guide, and control board together. Rotate the control board so that the original mount points for the clickers are facing backwards.",
            "Wire and glue LEDs under the clicker pads and behind each pad. Create a physical control circuit with a variable resistor and a switch to control the LEDs.",
            "Construct a base for the mouse from wood (or other chosen material), ensuring it fits the mouse components and provides a comfortable palm rest. Cut, whittle, and sand the base to the desired shape.",
            "Spray paint the base with several layers of black and green paint, sanding between coats for a smooth finish. Allow it to dry completely.",
            "Carefully glue the assembled mouse interface to the painted base, ensuring a comfortable and ergonomic position."
        ]
    }
